         b'  <!-- Hack to open external links in a new tab. -->\n           '
         b'             <p><a href="img/GuillaumeBouchardChamechaude.jpg" style'
         b'="cursor: default">\n    <img id="portrait" src="img/GuillaumeBou'
         b'chard.jpg"\n        alt="Guillaume at the top of Chamechaude in C'
         b'hartreuse montains, France"/>\n</a>\nI&rsquo;m Guillaume Bouchard,'
         b' Founder and Director of <a target="_blank" href="http://bloomsbury.'
         b'ai/">Bloomsbury-AI</a>, an early-stage company that enables everybod'
         b'y to teach what they know to the computer through a written conversa'
         b'tion. I&rsquo;m also associate researcher in the <a target="_blank" '
         b'href="http://mr.cs.ucl.ac.uk/">Machine Reading team</a> at  <a targe'
         b't="_blank" href="http://www.ucl.ac.uk/">University College London</a'
         b'> (UCL). Previously, I worked 11 years at <a target="_blank" href="h'
         b'ttp://www.xrce.xerox.com/About-XRCE/People/Guillaume-Bouchard">Xerox'
         b' Research Centre Europe</a> in Grenoble, France. I&rsquo;m passionat'
         b'e about <a target="_blank" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machi'
         b'ne_learning">Machine Learning</a>\nand <a target="_blank" href="h'
         b'ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_language_processing">Natural La'
         b'nguage Processing</a> (NLP). Since many years, my unique goal is to '
         b'replace programming languages with natural language, as shown in the'
         b'se videos: <a target="_blank" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v='
         b'sKZD8huxjZ0">Playfair AI summit 2015 (20 minutes)</a> and <a target='
         b'"_blank" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N0mRn1bQyzU">Entrepre'
         b'neur First Demo Day 2016 (5 minutes)</a>. </p>\n\n<p>My research i'
         b'nterests are closely related to the mathematical modelling of the wo'
         b'rld, especially when this helps to \nsolve real worl problems. I&'
         b'rsquo;m a big fan of:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><em>variational inference</e'
         b'm>: how to transform an intractable integral into an optimization pr'
         b'oblem. Classically, people use a method called Variational Bayes (VB'
         b') which is based on Jensen inequality, but I found a <a target="_bla'
         b'nk" href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1506.06100">new way</a> of doing usin'
         b'g Holder inequality that has much nicer theoretical properties. </li'
         b'>\n<li><em>stochastic optimization</em>:  using randomization tec'
         b'hniques to learn faster. In particular the concepts of <em><a target'
         b'="_blank" href="http://arxiv.org/abs/1506.09016">learning to sample<'
         b'/a></em> and <em>learning to optimize</em> seem to be really promisi'
         b'ng research topics, </li>\n<li><em>factorization model</em>: why '
         b'spectral theory appear naturally in many different areas and why emb'
         b'edding models can the seen as <a target="_blank" href="http://www.aa'
         b'ai.org/ocs/index.php/SSS/SSS15/paper/view/10257">good prior for logi'
         b'cal reasoning</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>In natural language processing'
         b', I have been interested for many years in flexible models that can '
         b'learn from a huge amount of \ndata. The hope is to automatically '
         b'learn general facts about the world, without having to specify an in'
         b'termediary representation, such as grammatical classes or ontologies'
         b'. This means:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><em>language models</em>: a generati'
         b've model of text, this can take many different form, but basically, '
         b'a language model gives you a high score for sentences that are plaus'
         b'ible.</li>\n<li><em>machine reading</em>: this can be viewed as a'
         b' question-answering system where there is some extra information, su'
         b'ch as questions about a short story, science exams questions. The re'
         b'al reason why I&rsquo;m interested in this techniques is that questi'
         b'on-answering is the equivalent of &ldquo;debugging&rdquo; when you w'
         b'rite software code, but this makes life so much easier when the comp'
         b'uter speaks your language (and adapts to your language as well&helli'
         b'p;).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you share any of my research interests, d'
         b'o have a look at my <a href="/publications.html">list of publication'
         b's</a> since 2015 and if you have questions regarding my previous and'
         b'/or current research, feel free to contact <a href="/contact.html">m'
         b'e</a>. I&rsquo;m part of the <a target="_blank" href="http://mr.cs.u'
         b'cl.ac.uk/">UCL Machine Reading Group</a> lead by <a target="_blank" '
         b'href="http://www.riedelcastro.org/">Sebastian Riedel</a>\nin the '
         b'<a target="_blank" href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/">Department of Com'
         b'puter Science</a>. I received a PhD in 2004 from Institut National d'
         b'e Recherche en Automatique et Informatique (<a target="_blank" href='
         b'"http://www.inria.fr/en/">INRIA</a>) and <a target="_blank" href="ht'
         b'tps://www.ujf-grenoble.fr/?language=en">University Joseph Fourier</a'
         b'>.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n    <div id="selected_pubs">\n        <h3>\n   '
